  "prompt": "Why is Bogota cold?",
  "response": "Bogota, the capital of Colombia, is cold due to several geographical factors:\n\n1. Elevation: Bogota is located at approximately 2,640 meters (8,660 feet) above sea level in the Andes Mountains, which creates a high-altitude, cool climate.\n\n2. Proximity to the Equator: Despite being near the equator, its high elevation keeps temperatures low, with average temperatures ranging from 9-20\u00b0C (48-68\u00b0F).\n\n3. Mountain climate: The Andes Mountain range significantly influences Bogota's climate, creating cooler temperatures compared to lower-altitude regions in Colombia.\n\n4. Latitude: Its location near the equator means it receives consistent sunlight year-round, but the altitude negates the typical heat associated with equatorial regions.\n\n5. Atmospheric conditions: The high-altitude location means thinner air, which contributes to cooler temperatures and more rapid heat loss.\n\nThese factors combine to create Bogota's characteristically cool climate, making it feel more like a temperate mountain city than a tropical location, despite its equatorial position.",
